{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is at module interaction: filesystem discovery + filename parsing/sorting + DB apply order recording. A unit test of sort logic alone can pass while runner wiring still applies out of order.","test_description":"Create a temp `migrations/` directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., `002_b.sql`, `010_c.sql`, `001_a.sql`) where each file inserts its id into a DB table. Run the real runner against a test Postgres DB, then assert inserted rows and `_migrations` records are in ascending numeric-prefix order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior depends on persisted DB metadata (`_migrations`) and runner re-entry logic across runs. Mocking DB state can hide real schema/query mismatches.","test_description":"Use real migration files where one migration has a visible side effect (e.g., insert sentinel row with unique constraint). Run runner once, then run it again against the same test DB. Assert the side effect occurred only once and `_migrations` has one record per file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Rollback/stop behavior is a transactional DB+runner interaction. Unit tests can verify error branching but cannot reliably validate transaction rollback semantics.","test_description":"Prepare three migrations: first makes a change, second has multiple statements with one intentional SQL error after an initial write, third would make a detectable change. Run runner on real test Postgres. Assert second migration leaves no partial writes, third migration was not applied, and `_migrations` only contains successful prior migrations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The behavior explicitly targets concurrent separate processes. Real inter-process timing/locking and DB coordination can fail in ways in-process mocks or single-process integration tests miss.","test_description":"Spawn two independent runner subprocesses simultaneously against the same Postgres DB and same migration directory. Include migrations with observable side effects and uniqueness guards. Wait for both to finish; assert each migration appears once in `_migrations` and side effects occurred exactly once total.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is startup sequencing across DB schema initialization and migration execution modules. A unit test of bootstrap function can miss real ordering/transaction issues.","test_description":"Start with a fresh Postgres schema lacking `_migrations`. Use first migration that would fail if `_migrations` bookkeeping is missing (or validate through DB state immediately after run). Execute runner and assert `_migrations` exists and first migration is successfully tracked, proving metadata table creation happened before application.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
